body:
> Can you attach an example that shows the issue?  

I have the following code, in a file called adder.sv, that implements a very basic 4-bit adder:

```
module fa4 (input logic [3:0] a, b, input logic ci, output logic [3:0] s, output logic co);
  logic [2:0] c;
  fa f1 (.a(a[0]), .b(b[0]), .ci(ci),   .s(s[0]), .co(c[0]));
  fa f2 (.a(a[1]), .b(b[1]), .ci(c[0]), .s(s[1]), .co(c[1]));
  fa f3 (.a(a[2]), .b(b[2]), .ci(c[1]), .s(s[2]), .co(c[2]));
  fa f4 (.a(a[3]), .b(b[3]), .ci(c[2]), .s(s[3]), .co(co));
endmodule

module fa (input logic a, b, ci, output logic s, co);
  assign s = a ^ b ^ ci;
  assign co = a&b | a&ci | b&ci;
endmodule
```

I run the command `verilator --cc adder.sv`, expecting it to Verilate without warnings, but it throws the following one:

```
%Warning-UNOPTFLAT: adder.sv:2:15: Signal unoptimizable: Feedback to clock or circular logic: 'fa4.c'
    2 |   logic [2:0] c;
      |               ^
                    ... Use "/* verilator lint_off UNOPTFLAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
                    adder.sv:2:15:      Example path: fa4.c
                    adder.sv:11:13:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    adder.sv:9:50:      Example path: fa4.__Vcellout__f2__co
                    adder.sv:4:52:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    adder.sv:2:15:      Example path: fa4.c
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```

I assume that Verilator sees the 3-bit intermediate carry-out "c" bus being used as both the input and output to a module, and throws this warning.  However, I'm using c[0] as the input, and c[1] as the output, so I didn't think that would constitute circular logic.

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

I have tested this on both Verilator 4.200 and 4.035 devel.

> Would you be willing to try to fix Verilator yourself with assistance?

Unfortunately, I do not have the technical expertise required to fix this problem myself.  I apologize if the warning is also just due to a lack of understanding on my part.
